title: For Sale:  380 ACP ammo for sale FS 250 rounds Two lots
postcontent:
I have two lots of two different kinds of 380ACP ammo for sale. Both are consisting of 5 boxes or 250 rounds total. They are all FMJ ball ammo in brass casing and are both reloadables. 

First is the RWS Sport line (Hungarian I believe). It is 95gr and shoots wonderful out of all my guns (more on that later). Second is the Sellir and Bellot aka S&B (Czech) and it is 92gr and again great to shoot. Personally I think it shoots a little hot but I always get consistent grouping to the point I think it is as good as the corbon defensive rounds.

Now as for the prices. If you buy both lots I will sell it for $210 which saves you $10. Also, before anyone start getting on my case for selling these for $22/Box I took the liberty of taking a couple of photos from Wal-Mart for references. The first picture isfor the WWB 380 and it is $22.47/box which is $24.29/box after 8.1% sales tax.

As for quality of the ammunitions. Some will argue WWB or other U.S. brands are superior in quality. Well folks, I am here to tell you that is incorrect. I currently own four different 380acp caliber pistols including two P232, PPK/S, and  P238, so I consider myself a sort of connoisseur. Not remington (junk, at least in 380), not WWB (two ftf in my p232) but rather the Europeans are better at manufacturing these rounds than we do. There's a big reason why 9mm kurz are written on all the boxes and that's because 380's are what police and civilian uses all around the world (look it up). Simply it is a much more popular catridge over there than over here. And these two manufactures are great at what they do. 

Enough rants and history lesson, if interested please leave a contact number with your email and how you want to be contacted. Thanks for looking

title: For Sale:  5.56 x 45mm (.223 Rem) Unique Frangible ammo 200 rds sealed battle pack
postcontent:
I have a unique item.  This is a sealed battle pack of 200 rounds of Hirtenberger Short Range Lead Free Ammo.  I have read many different stories on the "net" about it's original purpose.  Some say nuclear power plants, some say submarines, some say a gun range imported a ton of it because it didn't damage their backstop, etc. etc.
"Janes" lists the ammo as the following: Frangible short-range ball: 1.8g bullet (that's 28grains) consists of approximately 80% copper and 20% plastic; MV 1,050 m/s; maximum range 750 m; effective range 180 m; specially designed to function in automatic weapons up to 600 rds/min; also available with primers free of heavy metal (lead, antimony, barium)
Anyone who tells you this is a training bullet is not reading the specs correctly because 1050 m/s is over 3000ft/sec and an effective range of 180 meters (about 200 yards) means it's lethal at that range.  In military terms, yes, that's short range for a rifle.
It's a brass case cartridge with a copper sabot wrapping a black plastic projectile with a truncated cone  I opened one of the battle packs and can show you what they look like, but will not open the sealed battle pack that is for sale.  If you want to open it on the spot after you pay for it, I will give you your money back if it's not 100% what I am advertising.  Comes in an olive drab vinyl battle pack with a built in carry handle.  I'm 90% certain the brass is reloadable.

IT IS NOT TRAINING AMMO ! !  I guarantee it is quite lethal and should never be fired at a live target.  Per the specs it's about the same weight as an ultra high velocity 22LR like CCI Stinger, but at about 1000ft/sec higher velocity.

This link has photos of someones packs and discusses the round.  They are not my photos but mine look identical with identical markings.  http://www.ar15.com/archive/topic.html?b=3&f=16&t=484961 
As you can see, this stuff was about $1/round before the craziness.

I'm asking $180.

title: For Sale:  1942 Mosin Nagant - Beautiful!
postcontent:
I have a 1942 Mosin Nagant made in Izhevsk. It's a round receiver, war-time manufacture, which means the receiver was milled with less attention to finish. As a result, the more aesthetic features such as the "low-wall" milling and smooth finish were not performed in the interest of producing more rifles, more quickly, as the Soviets had that whole Nazi invasion thing to worry about.

Some people prefer the pre-war rifles because they're prettier, some people like the war-time rifles because they represent a response to a very specific threat. (Some even think the war-time rifles were built more sloppily, but there's no evidence to support that. Externally, superficially only, they aren't made to the same standard. They function every bit as well.)

Now you can run down to the local store and (provided they have them) pick up a virtually identical rifle for less. But that rifle will come caked in cosmoline. If you're not familiar with cosmoline and, more importantly, the chore of its removal, you're in for a real treat. And by treat I mean "endeavor likely to prompt you to learn how to cuss fluently in Russian if you don't know how already." It gets into every little nook, cranny, soaks into the stock... you name it.

And that's what sets this rifle apart. Pictures do not do it justice. It is cleaned up and ready for the dance. I've stripped it down to individual components, gone through and removed all the cosmoline, cleaned and lightly polished the chamber, checked the head space and it fully passes, reassembled and lightly oiled everything inside and out, and then just to be certain she was every bit the Russian beauty she was meant to be, I completely refinished the stock.

The reddish shellac they used to give these rifles their distinctive color is gone. I stained the wood back to the original color, then sealed it with polyurethane. Now we can see the beautiful grain of the stock. All the markings or "cartouches" are still there, I didn't touch them. I put a lot of effort into maintaining the character of this war horse - she's almost certainly seen battle in WW2 and it didn't seem right to erase the little dings and such she picked up along the way.

I'm willing to listen to offers, but don't try the "my buddy saw this at a gun show for $150, can you do that?" line. A: No he didn't. B: If by some stroke of luck you saw a Mosin for anything near that price it was caked with cosmoline and in who knows what kind of condition. Let me be clear: this rifle came out of a crate, just like any other, but it's not in that class anymore. She's ready to shoot and won't sweat cosmoline when you shoot it.

Comes with the tool kit (no canvas pouch) NUMBERS MATCHING bayonet (the rifle is also numbers-matching, but the magazine floorplate is a forced-match), but no sling. Yes, there's a sling on it in the picture, but that actually belongs to my "main" Mosin. I *might* part with it, but you'll have to talk me into that. Roll for charisma.

title: For Sale:  Inland M1 Paratrooper Carbine .30cal
postcontent:
This is an Inland Mfg.\ Division Of General Motors Produced Paratrooper M1 Carbine in A1 condition.  This is a 30 caliber semi auto rifle. I am including 2 clips and the original sling strap. It has a slight blemish on the front stock where the butt plate hits when the stock is folded, common on all of these models.  This is a type II according to Blue Book and has no bayonet lug and an adjustable rear sight.  This seems to be the rare model.  I have seen lots of type I and III but not II.  Last Type II I saw, sold here for $4200.00.  Bore is perfect and rifle has been cleaned and maintained since its purchased.  I have only fired it on 2 or 3 occasions.

This is an excerpt from Blue Book with the pricing for this carbine showing the value and percent quality. 
M1 A1 Paratrooper Carbine Type II

Values assume original guns with adj. rear sight and no bayonet lug.
